04682nam a22005775i 9780822391562DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223915627 a10.1515/97808223915622doi  a(DE-B1597)553681  a(OCoLC)456467943  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aBX1396.4 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a323/.042083509441 aWhitney, Susan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMobilizing Youth :bCommunists and Catholics in Interwar France /cSusan Whitney. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (332 p.) :b13 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Politics of Age and Generation in French Communism, 1920-1931 -- t2. Building a Communist Youth Organization -- t3. Age, Generation, and Catholic Anticommunism: The Emergence of the J.O.C. -- t4. Rereading the J.O.C. through the Lens of Gender: Young Women and the J.O.C.F. -- t5. Youth and the Emergence of Communist Antifascist Politics -- t6. Embracing the Status Quo: Communists, Young People, and Popular Front Politics -- t7. Refusing la main tendue: Catholics, the J.O.C. , and the Challenge of Communist Popular Front Politics -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography of Primary Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Mobilizing Youth, Susan B. Whitney examines how youth moved to the forefront of French politics in the two decades following the First World War. In those years Communists and Catholics forged the most important youth movements in France. Focusing on the competing efforts of the two groups to mobilize the young and harness generational aspirations, Whitney traces the formative years of the Young Communists and the Young Christian Workers, including their female branches. She analyzes the ideologies of the movements, their major campaigns, their styles of political and religious engagement, and their approaches to male and female activism. As Whitney demonstrates, the recasting of gender roles lay at the heart of Catholic efforts and became crucial to Communist strategies in the mid-1930s.Moving back and forth between the constantly shifting tactics devised to mobilize young people and the circumstances of their lives, Whitney gives special consideration to the context in which the youth movements operated and in which young people made choices. She traces the impact of the First World War on the young and on the formulation of generation-based political and religious identities, the role of work and leisure in young people's lives and political mobilization, the impact of the Depression, the importance of Soviet ideas and intervention in French Communist youth politics, and the state's attention to youth after the victory of France's Popular Front government in 1936. Mobilizing Youth concludes by inserting the era's youth activists and movements into the complicated events of the Second World War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aChurch work with youthxCatholic ChurchxHistoryy20th century. 0aChurch work with youthzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aCommunism and ChristianityxCatholic ChurchxHistoryy20th century. 0aCommunism and ChristianityzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822391562zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822391562423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822391562.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  